issue.title: Huge amount of managed allocations in C# API

repository.name: onnxruntime
repository.description: ONNX Runtime: cross-platform, high performance ML inferencing and training accelerator

issue.body:
**Describe the bug**
This is a performance issue. The C# API is unfortunately poorly designed and implemented when it comes to managed allocations for each `InferenceSession.Run`. There is no zero managed allocations path, this is sorely needed for high performance/latency sensitive scenarios.

**Urgency**
We need this within a month. It is likely we will have to do our own C# P/Invoke around the C API to achieve our goals. Long term we would very much like this in here of course :).

**System information**
- OS Platform and Distribution (e.g., Linux Ubuntu 16.04): Windows 10 64-bit
- ONNX Runtime installed from (source or binary): Source since we needed TensorRT support
- ONNX Runtime version: 1.1.0
- Visual Studio version (if applicable): 2019
- GCC/Compiler version (if compiling from source): MSVC 2019
- CUDA/cuDNN version: 10.1, 7
- GPU model and memory: 2060 Super

**To Reproduce**
Simply run a an inference loop in say BDN and measure number of managed allocations.

**Expected behavior**
A zero allocation path for `Run` e.g. by reusing instances and outputting into existing instances.

**Screenshots**
Profiling in VS2019 clearly shows the problem. Of about 1.3M allocations 1.1M are from OnnxRuntime, hence we have about 6-7x more allocations due to OnnxRuntime. This causes GC pauses above our budget. All the below allocations are from calling `Run` which is not great.

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/10798831/71622894-26f96e80-2bd9-11ea-88cf-e92ccd36936e.png)

**Additional context**
Looking at the source for the C# API there seems to be a lot of opportunity to improve this, but the ideal here is to have an API design that allows a zero managed allocation path. Additionally, it would be and is generally advisable that for these kinds of "wrappers" that the underlying C API is exposed in it's raw form, not hidden from advanced users. C API is stable, there is no reason to hide it as such, other than a hand-holding philosophy. :)

Anyone using OnnxRuntime from C# will benefit from this. In a broader context this would relate to how an API can be designed and implemented for high performance scenarios incl. #2754 

Additionally, a proper release for TensorRT is needed too. In many ways a more modular plug-in based model for distribution and packaging seems relevant. 

cc: @tannergooding
